==Ethnic groups== {{bar box |title=Ethnic groups of Cayman Islands <ref name="CIAPAPUANEWGUINEA">{{cite web|url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/cj.html|title=Central America and Caribbean :: CAYMAN ISLANDS|publisher= CIA The World Factbook}}</ref> |titlebar=#ddd |left1=Ethnic groups |right1=percent |float=left |bars= {{bar percent|[[Multiracial|Mixed]]|Blue|40}} {{bar percent|[[Afro-Caribbean|Black]]|Yellow|20}} {{bar percent|[[White people|White]] |Orange|20}} {{bar percent| [[Expatriate|Expatriates of various ethnic groups]] |Green|20}} }} {{clear}} Although many [[Caribbean]] islands were initially populated by [[Amerindian]] groups such as the [[Taíno]] and [[Island Caribs|Caribs]], no evidence of this has been found in the Cayman Islands. Therefore, native Caymanians do not have any Amerindian heritage from their own islands; however, a significant number of Jamaicans have settled in the Cayman Islands over the years, so they and their descendants may have some Amerindian blood via Jamaica. [[Slavery]] was less common on the Cayman Islands than in many other parts of the Caribbean, resulting in a more even division of [[Africa]]n and [[Europe]]an ancestry. Those of mixed race make up 40% of the population, with blacks and whites following at 20% each. The remaining 20% belong to various immigrant ethnic groups.
According to CIA factbook of 2013, Caymanian people of mixed-race of mixed black African and white European ancestry are the plurality ethnic group in the [[Cayman Islands]], accounting for 40% of the country's population, with white 20%, black 20%, and expatriates of various ethnic groups 20%.<ref name="CIAPAPUANEWGUINEA"/>
==Language== {{bar box |title=Languages of Cayman Islands (2010)<ref name="CIAPAPUANEWGUINEA"/> |titlebar=#ddd |left1=Languages |right1=percent |float=left |bars= {{bar percent|[[English language|English]]|Blue|90.9}} {{bar percent|[[Spanish language|Spanish]] |Orange|4}} {{bar percent|[[Filipino language|Filipino]]|Yellow|3.3}} {{bar percent|Other |Green|1.7}} {{bar percent|Unspecified |Green|0.1}} }} {{clear}} The official language of the Cayman Islands is English. Islanders' accents retain elements passed down from English, Scottish, and Welsh settlers (among others) in a language variety known as [[Cayman Creole]]. Caymanians of Jamaican origin speak in their own vernacular (see [[Jamaican Creole]] and [[Jamaican English]]). It is also quite commonplace to hear some residents converse in Spanish as many citizens have relocated from Latin America to work and live on Grand Cayman. The Latin American nations with greatest representation are Honduras, Cuba, Colombia, Nicaragua, and the Dominican Republic. Spanish speakers comprise approximately between 10-12% of the population and is predominantly of the [[Caribbean Spanish|Caribbean dialect]]. Tagalog is spoken by about 5% of inhabitants most of whom are Filipino residents on work permits.
==Religion== {{bar box |title=Religion of Cayman Islands (2010)<ref name="CIAPAPUANEWGUINEA"/> |titlebar=#ddd |left1=Religions |right1=percent |float=left |bars= {{bar percent|[[Protestant]]|Violet|67.8}} {{bar percent|[[Roman Catholic ]]|red|14.1}} {{bar percent|None|Blue|9.3}} {{bar percent|Other|Blue|7}} {{bar percent|[[Jehovah's Witness]] |blue| 1.1}} {{bar percent|Unspecified |red| 0.7}} }} {{bar box |title=Religion of Cayman Islands, detailed (2010)<ref name="CIAPAPUANEWGUINEA"/> |titlebar=#ddd |left1=Religions |right1=percent |float=left |bars= {{bar percent|[[Church of God in Christ|Church of God]]|Violet|22.6}} {{bar percent|[[Roman Catholic ]]|red|14.1}} {{bar percent|[[Seventh-day Adventist]]|Yellow|9.4}} {{bar percent|None|Blue|9.3}} {{bar percent|[[Baptist]]|green| 8.3}} {{bar percent| [[Presbyterian]]/[[United Church]] |Silver| 8.6}} {{bar percent|[[Pentecostal]] |grey|7.1}} {{bar percent|Other |Blue|7}} {{bar percent|[[Non-denominational]]|yellow| 5.3}} {{bar percent|[[Anglicanism|Anglican]] |Pink| 4.1}} {{bar percent| [[Holiness movement|Wesleyan Holiness]] |black|2.4}} {{bar percent|[[Jewish]] |silver| 1.5}} {{bar percent|[[Jehovah's Witness]] |blue| 1.1}} {{bar percent|Unspecified |red| 0.7}} }} {{clear}} The predominant religion on the Cayman Islands is [[Christianity]]. Collectively, Protestants account for 67.8%, while the Roman Catholic Church accounts for 14.1%. Denominations practiced include [[United Church in Jamaica and the Cayman Islands|United Church]], [[Church of God (Cleveland, Tennessee)|Church of God]], [[Anglican Church]], [[Baptist Church]], [[Roman Catholic Church]], [[Seventh-day Adventist Church]], and [[Pentecostal Church]]. Roman Catholic churches are [[St. Ignatius Church, George Town]] and [[Stella Maris Church, Cayman Brac]]. Many citizens are deeply religious, regularly going to church. Ports are closed on Sundays and Christian holidays. There are places of worship in George Town for [[Jehovah's Witnesses]] and followers of the [[Bahá'í faith]]. The Cayman Islands also hosts a growing [[Jewish]] community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chabadcaymanislands.com/|title=Chabad Cayman Jewish Community|website=Chabadcaymanislands.com|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref>
